$CATEGORY: CIT/M5/week-14/14-6-the-react-pattern-reason-act-observe-repeat

::q1:: A student argues that an AI agent should use chain-of-thought reasoning — writing out its thinking step by step — without ever calling any external tools. What is the core problem with this approach that the ReAct pattern was designed to fix? {
~The agent issues tool calls in the wrong order because it has no mechanism to sequence parallel results. The loop breaks down when multiple Observations arrive out of order and the agent cannot match them to the right Action.#No — this approach calls no tools at all, so out-of-order tool results are not the issue. The failure that ReAct addresses is factual inaccuracy, not sequencing.
~The agent's reasoning trace is hidden from developers because chain-of-thought output is suppressed by default. Without a visible log, the team cannot audit the agent's decisions or understand why it chose each step.#No — chain-of-thought reasoning is written out and fully visible in the context window. The failure is about factual accuracy, not the visibility of the reasoning trace.
=The agent produces fluent, confident answers that are factually wrong because it never checks real-world facts with a tool. It reasons entirely from its training memory, which may be outdated or incorrect for the specific question asked.#Correct — reasoning alone can hallucinate. Without grounding each step in a real tool result, the model is guessing from parametric memory, and that guess can be wrong even when it sounds authoritative (corpus §5.1).
~The agent loops forever because chain-of-thought reasoning provides no stopping criterion. Without an explicit Final Answer stage, the model keeps producing more reasoning steps rather than returning a response to the user.#No — an infinite loop from missing stopping criteria is a separate implementation problem. The specific failure mode that motivated ReAct is producing factually wrong answers, not running indefinitely.
#### Tests LO1 — why ReAct combines reasoning and acting rather than using reasoning alone (corpus §5.1).
}

::q2:: Which of the following correctly lists all four stages of a single ReAct cycle, in the order they occur? {
=Thought → Action → Observation → repeat (or Final Answer). The agent first writes its reasoning, then calls a tool, then reads the tool's real result, and then either loops back to write another Thought or ends the task with a Final Answer.#Correct — Thought precedes Action, the Observation follows the Action, and the loop either repeats or ends with a Final Answer (corpus §5.2).
~Observation → Thought → Action → Final Answer. The agent first gathers an Observation from the environment, then reasons about it in a Thought, then takes an Action, and finally produces a Final Answer once enough Observations have been collected.#No — an Observation is the result of an Action, so it cannot come before the Thought and Action that produce it. The cycle always starts with a Thought.
~Action → Thought → Observation → Final Answer. The agent acts first to gather data from a tool, then writes a Thought to interpret the result, then receives the Observation from the system, and finally decides on a Final Answer.#No — the Action comes after the Thought, not before it. In ReAct the agent reasons explicitly first and then decides what action to take, so Thought always precedes Action.
~Thought → Observation → Action → repeat. The agent reasons first, then receives an Observation from the environment, then takes an Action based on that Observation, and loops until it has gathered enough information to answer.#No — an Observation is produced by an Action and cannot arrive before the Action is taken. The correct sequence is Thought → Action → Observation, not Thought → Observation → Action.
#### Tests LO2 — naming and ordering the four stages of a ReAct cycle (corpus §5.2).
}

::q3:: In the Eiffel Tower worked trace from the corpus, the agent uses two tools before finishing. After the second Observation ("137") arrives from the calculator, what does the agent produce next? {
~Another Action calling a third tool to verify the arithmetic result. The agent treats a single tool result as unconfirmed and checks the calculator output against a backup source before it will trust the number.#No — the agent already has both required facts: the completion year and the arithmetic difference. There is no remaining gap in knowledge, so a third tool call is unnecessary.
=A Thought explicitly stating that the agent now has all the required information, followed immediately by a Final Answer. The Thought signals that no further tool calls are needed, and the agent exits the loop by returning the answer to the user.#Correct — the agent reasons that both pieces of data are in hand (Thought), then produces a Final Answer rather than another Action, which ends the loop (corpus §5.5).
~A new Observation appended by the system to confirm that the calculation completed without errors. The system adds a status message before the agent can proceed, because tool results must be validated before the LLM core is allowed to use them.#No — Observations are only appended to the log in response to an Action. The agent has not issued another Action, so no new Observation can be added at this point.
~A restart of the entire loop from the original question with a fresh conversation log. The agent clears its prior Thoughts and Observations to prevent context-window overflow before producing its final answer.#No — the ReAct loop never restarts from scratch. The conversation log is cumulative; each new Thought builds on all prior Thoughts and Observations from the same task.
#### Tests LO3 — tracing a complete multi-step ReAct example and identifying each stage (corpus §5.5).
}

::q4:: A developer's ReAct agent returned a wrong answer on a multi-step question. They open the agent's log to find the source of the error. Which feature of ReAct makes it possible to pinpoint the exact step where the reasoning broke down? {
~The agent automatically retries tool calls that return unexpected results and logs each retry with a new Observation. A developer can read the retry log to identify which specific tool call eventually produced the correct data.#No — automatic retries are not part of the core ReAct pattern. That is a separate error-handling mechanism and is not the feature that makes ReAct inherently debuggable.
~The agent assigns a numeric confidence score to every Observation before including it in the next Thought, and those scores are stored in the log. A developer can find the exact Observation where the agent assigned too high a confidence to a wrong result.#No — ReAct does not include a confidence-scoring step. Observations are treated as authoritative facts from external tools; the loop contains no mechanism for scoring or filtering them.
~The agent enforces a hard maximum on the number of cycles and logs a timeout error when that limit is reached. By checking which cycle triggered the timeout, a developer can narrow down where the agent failed to make progress.#No — a cycle-count safety limit prevents infinite loops but does not reveal why reasoning went wrong. It tells the developer the loop ran too long, not where the logic error occurred.
=Every Thought is written explicitly into the conversation log, so a developer can read the agent's reasoning before each Action and find exactly where the logic went wrong. The Thought trail pinpoints the faulty step without requiring any additional debugging instrumentation.#Correct — because Thought lines are explicit and permanently logged, a developer can trace the full decision trail and pinpoint the exact cycle where the agent reasoned incorrectly (corpus §5.3, §5.7).
#### Tests LO4 — explaining why explicit Thought lines improve debuggability (corpus §5.3, §5.7).
}

::q5:: The ReAct pattern was motivated by two specific failure modes observed in earlier agent designs. Which answer correctly names both failure modes? {
=Producing hallucinated answers when the agent reasons with chain-of-thought alone and never calls tools, and being nearly impossible to debug when the agent calls tools without writing any reasoning trace. ReAct fixes the first by grounding each step in a tool Observation, and the second by logging every Thought explicitly.#Correct — chain-of-thought alone produces plausible but unverified answers (hallucination); action-only loops hide why decisions were made (opacity). ReAct fixes both by interleaving Thoughts with tool calls (corpus §5.1).
~Overloading a single cycle with too many tool calls, and generating Thought lines so long that they exhaust the context window. Both problems degrade performance in practice: overloaded cycles produce disordered Observations, and verbose Thoughts waste the token budget needed for later cycles.#No — these are practical efficiency concerns about token usage and call volume. They are not the foundational failure modes that the ReAct paper identified as motivating the interleaved design.
~Selecting the wrong tool from the available set, and running the loop for more cycles than necessary to complete the task. Choosing the wrong tool produces misleading Observations, while excess cycles waste compute time and increase response latency for the end user.#No — tool selection errors and unnecessary loop iterations are deployment-level tuning problems. They are not the two core failure modes that motivated the original ReAct design of alternating Thoughts and tool calls.
~Forgetting earlier Observations after several cycles because they fall outside the context window, and calling the same tool twice with identical inputs. Both failures cause the agent to waste effort, potentially loop without making progress, and produce lower-quality answers.#No — context-window memory loss and redundant tool calls are real agent challenges, but they are not the failure modes that specifically motivated ReAct. The motivation was hallucination from reasoning-only agents and opacity from action-only agents.
#### Tests LO5 — describing the two failure modes that motivated ReAct (corpus §5.1).
}

::q6:: In a ReAct loop, what is an Observation, and who or what adds it to the conversation log? {
~An Observation is a short summary that the LLM core writes after re-reading its own Thought from the previous cycle. The model generates it to confirm its own understanding before deciding which Action to take next.#No — the LLM core writes Thoughts and Actions, not Observations. Observations come from outside the model and are added to the log by the agent system after a real tool call completes.
~An Observation is the Final Answer that the agent produces once it has gathered enough information across all its tool calls. The LLM core adds it to the log as the last entry in the conversation, signaling the system that the loop should stop.#No — that description is the Final Answer stage, which is distinct from an Observation. Observations occur after every individual tool call throughout the loop, not only at the very end.
=An Observation is the real result from a tool call — a search snippet or calculator output — added to the log by the agent system, not generated by the LLM core. It brings verified external data into the loop so the agent's next Thought is grounded in facts rather than model memory.#Correct — the Observation is external data from the tool (a search result, a calculation, a database row). The agent system appends it to the log; the LLM core did not generate it (corpus §5.2).
~An Observation is a confidence score that the agent system attaches to each tool result before returning it to the LLM core. High-scoring Observations are included in the next Thought, while low-scoring ones are discarded to prevent the agent from reasoning on unreliable data.#No — ReAct does not include a confidence-scoring step for tool results. The Observation is the raw output of the tool, and the agent treats it as an authoritative fact without any filtering or scoring.
#### Tests LO2 — describing what the Observation stage is and how it enters the log (corpus §5.2).
}
